{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b18ce911-f474-4eb8-aa7d-4f2de93b8d14","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\n# From your local machine:\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView** (Windows), or convert to speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n# Then open at https://speedscope.app\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or the `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` env var with `dotnet-dsrouter` for out-of-pod collection.\n- For a quick sanity check *before* tracing, `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` shows live CPU/GC metrics.\n- `--profile cpu-sampling` is lightweight (~5% overhead) and safe for production.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f204e03a-592e-4547-a3fc-65428f326206","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"942C:164D4D:18DC531:1C23FFB:69E81E51"},"id":"82301e19-bae7-4108-a233-e29cb8b72eaa","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:23.896Z","parentId":"701ba92e-8030-4dff-b1f8-c3f44a5545ae"}
